<h2><a name="while" id="while">while</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="kw1">while</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> condition <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
    statement<span class="sy0">-</span>list;
    <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>

The while keyword is used as a looping construct that will evaluate the
statement-list as long as condition is true. Note that if the condition starts
off as false, the statement-list will never be executed. (You can use a do loop
to guarantee that the statement-list will be executed at least once.) For
example:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">     bool done <span class="sy0">=</span> <span class="kw2">false</span>;
     <span class="kw1">while</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="sy0">!</span>done <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
       ProcessData<span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span>;
       <span class="kw1">if</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> StopLooping<span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
         done <span class="sy0">=</span> <span class="kw2">true</span>;
       <span class="br0">&#125;</span>
     <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>
Related Topics: <a href="break" class="wikilink1" title="keywords:break">break</a>, <a href="continue" class="wikilink1" title="keywords:continue">continue</a>, <a href="do" class="wikilink1" title="keywords:do">do</a>, <a href="for" class="wikilink1" title="keywords:for">for</a>, <a href="if" class="wikilink1" title="keywords:if">if</a>
</p>

